  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
      if (a[i] == b[j]) {
        cout << a[i] << " ";
        break;
      } 
    }
  }
}
```

The key points are:

- Nested loops to iterate through both arrays
- Check if current element in a matches any element in b. 
- If match found, print the element and break to avoid duplicates
- No extra arrays or data structures used

